page.title: 01The Hills S.W. of Partree
page.content: Most of the ground is high moorand where sheep are grazed with Beinn na greine, 417m, the highest. In the extreme east the ground falls steeply to mouth of River Varrigall and Loch Partree. The main road to Partree viage runs northward through this lowlying ground. To the west are 3 masts,one transmitting telvision pictures, a British Teecom radio link and a smaller mast used by local Electricity Board. On the slopes above the main road is Glen Varrigall Forest, owned by the Forestry Commision aand planted in mid 50s with a variety of conifers. A pleasant forestry walk allows the public access to northern end of this plantation.
